# image.env.example — TEMPLATE ONLY. NOT sourced by the build.
#
# This file is a reference / starting point. It is NEVER read by
# scripts/build.sh — the build sources image.env exclusively. If
# image.env doesn't exist, the build fails with a clear "copy this
# template" message. (Previous versions used this file as a silent
# fallback, but that masked config drift between dev local edits and
# CI's un-edited template.)
#
# First-time setup for a fork:
#   cp image.env.example image.env
#   $EDITOR image.env
#   git add image.env && git commit -m 'add image.env for <my-image>'
#
# Resolution order (increasing precedence) once image.env exists:
#   1. image.env          (committed canonical config — required)
#   2. Shell / CI env     (always wins, for pipeline overrides)
#
# image.env IS committed (intentionally — per-fork config travels with
# the code). Bamboo / GitLab CI plan vars take precedence over it, so
# put SECRETS (tokens, passwords) in plan vars only. Never commit
# tokens to image.env — both remotes (origin GitLab + GitHub mirror)
# would expose them.

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# UPSTREAM YOU'RE REBUILDING
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# The upstream tag IS our version. There is no separate internal
# semver — we rebuild upstream as-is (plus remediation + cert
# injection), and the pushed tag embeds the upstream tag plus the
# git commit SHA for build uniqueness:
#
#   <push-host>/<push-prefix>/<IMAGE_NAME>:<UPSTREAM_TAG>-<gitShort>
#
# The push host + prefix come from whichever backend you pick via
# REGISTRY_KIND (HARBOR_REGISTRY/HARBOR_PROJECT for harbor.sh, or
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST + ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF template for
# artifactory.sh). Example pushed tag:
#   harbor.example.com/apps/platform/nginx:1.25.3-alpine-a1b2c3d
#
# Harbor env-at-project layout. Top-level projects:
#   dev      — team build artifacts (retention: keep last 6)
#   prod     — promoted artifacts (immutable tags)
#   shared   — vendored base images, internal platform infra
#
# Team product images: CI builds push to dev/<team>/<image>; the
# promote job copies approved digests to prod/<team>/<image> via
# Harbor's native artifact-copy API. Same digest preserved.
#
# Vendored base images: push directly to shared/base/<image>.
#
# Renovate bumps UPSTREAM_TAG via the `# renovate:` hint below.
# Matches the tagging convention of the container-images monorepo.
#
# Variable naming (template vs monorepo):
#   Template uses UPSTREAM_REGISTRY + UPSTREAM_IMAGE + UPSTREAM_TAG
#   Monorepo uses SOURCE + TAG (combined registry/image path + version)
#   Both produce the same upstream reference at build time.

# Registry host + path prefix the upstream image lives at. Defaults
# to Docker Hub's library namespace. For air-gap / closed networks,
# override via the UPSTREAM_REGISTRY CI variable to point at your
# Artifactory proxy (dockerhub.artifactory.example.com/library).
UPSTREAM_REGISTRY="docker.io/library"

# Upstream image name (under UPSTREAM_REGISTRY).
UPSTREAM_IMAGE="nginx"


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  ▼  RENOVATE HINT  ▼   (load-bearing — read this before editing)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  The `# renovate:` line directly above UPSTREAM_TAG is what triggers
#  Renovate to auto-bump the version. Two rules to keep it working:
#
#    1. The hint MUST remain on the line immediately above UPSTREAM_TAG.
#       (Blank lines or other comments between them break the match.)
#    2. depName MUST match the upstream Docker Hub repo path —
#       i.e. "<UPSTREAM_REGISTRY>/<UPSTREAM_IMAGE>" minus the
#       "docker.io/" prefix. For library images that's "library/nginx",
#       not "nginx". Renovate matches on this exactly.
#
#  When forking, edit BOTH the depName below AND the UPSTREAM_TAG value.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# renovate: datasource=docker depName=library/nginx
UPSTREAM_TAG="1.25.3-alpine"

# Name of the image as pushed to your registry. The final push URL
# (built by whichever backend you select via REGISTRY_KIND) embeds
# this as the leaf, e.g.
#   harbor.example.com/apps/platform/nginx:<UPSTREAM_TAG>-<gitShort>
# If omitted, defaults to UPSTREAM_IMAGE. Override only if you're
# rebranding (e.g. rebuilding upstream "nginx" as "nginx-hardened"
# in your registry).
# IMAGE_NAME="nginx"

# Append the git short SHA to the pushed tag for build differentiation
# (e.g. "1.25.3-alpine-a1b2c3d"). Default true.
#
# Set to false (also accepts: False / FALSE / 0 / no / off) when
# UPSTREAM_TAG is a moving alias like "latest" or "stable" and you
# want the pushed tag to mirror it exactly — e.g. building
# nginx:latest → harbor.example.com/.../nginx:latest with NO suffix.
# WARNING with false: subsequent builds OVERWRITE the same tag in the
# registry. Cosign signatures still bind to the digest, so they remain
# valid, but the human-readable tag becomes ambiguous. Prefer true
# for prod images; false is mostly useful for dev "rolling" tags.
# APPEND_GIT_SHORT="true"

# Vendor name for the OCI image label `org.opencontainers.image.vendor`.
# Default "example.com" if unset. Override per-fork to your company name.
VENDOR="example.com"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ENRICHMENT FLAGS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Package upgrades and bespoke installs are NOT toggled here — they
# go directly in the Dockerfile's "FORK EDITS GO HERE" region. That
# moves CVE remediation, extra `apk add` lines, config drops, etc.
# to the file every fork already owns and edits. No DISTRO selector,
# no remediate stage, no scripts/remediate/ directory.

# Inject CA certificates from the repo's certs/ directory into the
# image trust store. When the CA_CERT CI variable is set at build
# time, scripts/build.sh writes its PEM content to certs/ and flips
# this to "true" automatically. The Dockerfile's certs-true stage is
# distro-agnostic (cat-append into both ca-certificates.crt and
# cert.pem, then best-effort update-ca-certificates).
INJECT_CERTS="false"

# USER value to restore at the end of the build. Cert injection runs
# as root (required for writing into /etc/ssl/), and the fork-edit
# region in the Dockerfile inherits that root context too. This is
# the UID/username the upstream image ran as — check with:
#   docker inspect <upstream> --format='{{.Config.User}}'
# For images whose entrypoint expects to start as root and drop privs
# itself (nginx, some database images), keep "root".
ORIGINAL_USER="root"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TOOL DOWNLOAD URLS (air-gap support)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# build.sh auto-installs `crane` if it's not on PATH (used for
# resolving the upstream image's digest for the OCI base.digest label).
# By default it derives a public GitHub release URL matching host
# OS/arch. Override here when GitHub is blocked and you've mirrored
# the tarball into Artifactory.
#
# Example air-gap value:
#   CRANE_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/generic-tools/crane/v0.20.2/go-containerregistry_Linux_x86_64.tar.gz"
# CRANE_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/generic-tools/crane/v0.20.2/go-containerregistry_Linux_x86_64.tar.gz"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# PUSH BACKEND SELECTOR
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Resolves to scripts/push-backends/<value>.sh. The chosen backend
# reads its own namespace of variables and ignores the others:
#
#   "harbor"      → scripts/push-backends/harbor.sh    (reads HARBOR_*)
#   "artifactory" → scripts/push-backends/artifactory.sh (reads ARTIFACTORY_*)
#
# Default is "harbor". Drop a new file in scripts/push-backends/ to
# add a new backend; each file owns its own var namespace.
#
# IMPORTANT: HARBOR_* and ARTIFACTORY_* are FULLY INDEPENDENT — they
# never default to or auto-derive from each other. Set ONLY the
# namespace that matches your REGISTRY_KIND; you can ignore the
# other section entirely.

# REGISTRY_KIND="harbor"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# HARBOR BACKEND  (only relevant when REGISTRY_KIND="harbor")
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Skip this whole section if you're using REGISTRY_KIND=artifactory.
# The Harbor backend reads ONLY HARBOR_* — it never inherits from
# ARTIFACTORY_* or any other namespace.
#
# In CI, set the password as a masked variable; everything else can
# live in image.env (committed) since hostnames + project paths
# aren't secrets.

# Destination registry host.
# HARBOR_REGISTRY="harbor.example.com"

# Destination project / path prefix under HARBOR_REGISTRY.
# Push URL becomes <HARBOR_REGISTRY>/<HARBOR_PROJECT>/<IMAGE_NAME>:<TAG>.
#
# ── Harbor folder-structure conventions ─────────────────────────────
# Harbor enforces ONE shape: <host>/<project>/<repo>:<tag>. There's no
# template choice (unlike Artifactory's 6 layouts) because Harbor has
# no virtual-repo / subdomain routing — the docker push URL IS the
# canonical address. The only real decision is HOW you organise
# HARBOR_PROJECT. Pick one of these patterns and stick to it across
# forks; consistency makes promotion + RBAC easier.
#
#   Pattern                        HARBOR_PROJECT example     When to use
#   ─────────────────────────────  ─────────────────────────  ─────────────
#   Per-image-class                "base-images"              Vendored upstream rebuilds vs.
#                                  "apps"                     first-party app images split.
#                                                             Project-level RBAC = "platform
#                                                             team writes base-images, app
#                                                             teams read them."
#
#   Per-environment (flat)         "dev"                      Promotion = copy digest from
#                                  "prod"                     dev/<image> → prod/<image>.
#                                  "staging"                  Same digest, different project
#                                                             retention policy.
#
#   Per-environment + team subdir  "dev/cdss"                 Multi-team, shared envs. Top-
#                                  "prod/cdss"                level project = env, subdir =
#                                                             team. RBAC at project root.
#
#   Per-team + environment subdir  "cdss/dev"                 Team owns its own project;
#                                  "cdss/prod"                env is just a path segment.
#                                                             Team-level RBAC.
#
#   Single shared project          "library"                  Tiny org, one team, no
#                                                             promotion ritual.
#
# Whichever pattern you pick, the SCRIPT is unchanged — only the
# HARBOR_PROJECT value differs. There's no template indirection
# because the convention is a value, not a structure.
# HARBOR_PROJECT="apps/platform"

# Harbor account with Push permission to HARBOR_PROJECT.
# HARBOR_USER="svc-cicd"

# Push password / robot token (CI-masked, never committed).
# HARBOR_PASSWORD="<harbor-cli-secret-or-robot-token>"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ARTIFACTORY BACKEND  (only relevant when REGISTRY_KIND="artifactory")
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Skip this whole section if you're using REGISTRY_KIND=harbor. The
# Artifactory backend reads ONLY ARTIFACTORY_* — it never inherits
# from HARBOR_* or any other namespace.
#
# The backend supports both JCR Free and Artifactory Pro — set
# ARTIFACTORY_PRO=true to enable Pro-tier features (project-scoped
# build info, jf docker push with module linkage, Xray build scan).

# ── Required (when REGISTRY_KIND=artifactory) ────────────────────

# Artifactory URL. Must include the https:// scheme.
# For JFrog Cloud: https://yourorg.jfrog.io
# ARTIFACTORY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com"

# User with Deploy rights.
#
# IMPORTANT — JFrog Cloud + docker login gotcha: this value MUST match
# the username encoded in your access token, NOT the user's login email.
# The two are often different on JFrog Cloud trials and SaaS:
#
#   - `jf config add` accepts email-form (API auth via token claim)
#   - `docker login` rejects email — needs the literal username that
#     the token's `sub` field encodes (commonly "admin" or a service-
#     account name like "svc-cicd")
#
# Find it for an existing access token:
#   echo "$TOKEN" | cut -d. -f2 | base64 -d 2>/dev/null | jq -r .sub
# Result looks like "jfac@<server-id>/users/<USERNAME>" — take the
# part after the last `/`. That's what docker login expects here.
#
# Symptom when wrong: docker login fails with "Wrong username was
# used" in the build job's log when REGISTRY_KIND=artifactory.
# ARTIFACTORY_USER="svc-cicd"

# Auth — token preferred; password works if tokens aren't available.
# Token format is a long base64-ish string (JWT or reference token);
# the password is whatever the user logs in to the UI with.
# ARTIFACTORY_TOKEN="eyJ2ZXIiOiIyIiwidHlwIjoiSldUIiwiYWxnIjoiUlMyNTYi..."
# ARTIFACTORY_PASSWORD="<svc-cicd-password>"

# Team acronym — short slug, referenced by the layout templates below
# (e.g. "platform", "cdss", "data"). Lowercase letters / digits /
# dashes only on JFrog Cloud.
# ARTIFACTORY_TEAM="platform"

# ── Pro tier ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set ARTIFACTORY_PRO=true to enable: jf docker push (layer/manifest
# module linkage), project-scoped build info, jf build-scan (Xray
# CVE analysis).

# ARTIFACTORY_PRO="false"

# Project key for --project flag. Defaults to ARTIFACTORY_TEAM when unset.
# Lowercase letters / digits / dashes only on JFrog Cloud (rejects
# uppercase). Pick a short slug that maps to a project you've created
# under Administration → Platform Configuration → Projects.
# ARTIFACTORY_PROJECT="platform"

# ── Optional ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Environment selector. "prod"/"production" → prod repo suffix,
# anything else → "local". Drives the default manifest-path template.
# ARTIFACTORY_ENVIRONMENT="dev"

# Docker push hostname — override for subdomain layouts.
# Defaults to the host portion of ARTIFACTORY_URL when unset.
# Examples: "artifactory.example.com" (path-routed),
#           "docker.artifactory.example.com" (subdomain-routed shared),
#           "myorg.jfrog.io" (JFrog Cloud).
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"

# Build info name. Default: ${IMAGE_NAME}-build (the -build suffix
# keeps build-info visually distinct from the image + packages in
# Artifactory's UI).
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_NAME="nginx-build"

# Build number. Defaults to CI_JOB_ID / CI_PIPELINE_ID / BUILD_NUMBER /
# bamboo_buildNumber / GITHUB_RUN_ID / UTC timestamp — whichever is
# set first. Override only if you want a custom build identifier.
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_NUMBER="2026.05.12-01"

# Extra ;-separated properties applied to the pushed manifest. Format
# is "key=value;key=value" — Artifactory shows them under Set Me Up
# → Properties on the artifact.
# ARTIFACTORY_PROPERTIES="security.scan=pending;approval.status=draft"

# Xray-indexed generic repo for SBOM upload (scripts/sbom-post.sh SINK 3).
# On Pro, Xray also generates SBOMs natively from the pushed image.
# Create the repo as Generic and add it to an Xray indexed-resources
# policy so uploaded .cdx.json files get scanned.
# ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_REPO="sboms-local"

# Plain generic Artifactory repo for SBOM archive upload (sbom-post.sh SINK 4).
# Same upload path shape (<repo>/<image>/<tag>/sbom.cdx.json) but NO Xray
# expectation — pure long-term archive for cross-team browsability. Can
# run alongside ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_REPO (different repo, different intent).
# Example: ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_ARCHIVE_REPO="newen-generic-dev-local"
# ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_ARCHIVE_REPO="<team>-generic-<env>-local"

# Generic repo for mirroring the Grype CVE DB. When set,
# scripts/mirror-grype-db.sh downloads the DB from grype.anchore.io
# and uploads to this repo; grype scans then pull from the mirror
# instead of the public CDN (air-gap support).
# ARTIFACTORY_GRYPE_DB_REPO="grype-db-local"

# ── Xray scan gates (Pro-only) ────────────────────────────────────
# The pre-scan and post-scan toggles are symmetric — you can enable
# either, both, or neither. The fail-mode flag applies to both.

# Pre-push scan via `jf docker scan` against the locally-tagged image,
# run INSIDE the build job by the push backend. The BUILD_ prefix
# distinguishes this from scripts/scan/xray-vuln.sh (which is a
# separate, standalone CI stage that scans an arbitrary ref). Same
# Xray engine, different pipeline placement.
#
# Combined with ARTIFACTORY_XRAY_FAIL_ON_VIOLATIONS=true, gates push
# itself — violations keep the image OUT of Artifactory entirely (vs.
# the post-push build-scan which gates promotion after upload). Uses
# only internal Xray endpoints — no outbound to anchore.io — making
# this the air-gap-friendly equivalent of the Grype stage. Adds
# ~10–60s to the critical path. Needs ARTIFACTORY_PROJECT (or TEAM)
# so Xray can match watches; without it the scan is informational.
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_XRAY_PRESCAN="false"

# Post-push `jf build-scan` run INSIDE the build job by the push
# backend (paired with the prescan above; same BUILD_ prefix means
# "happens during the build job, not as a separate scan stage").
# Default "false" — opt in only when a JFrog Pro / Xray licence is
# provisioned. Set "true" to enable; pair with
# ARTIFACTORY_XRAY_FAIL_ON_VIOLATIONS=true to gate promote/deploy
# jobs on a clean post-push scan.
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_XRAY_POSTSCAN="false"

# Policy-violation handling for BOTH pre and post scans (exit 3):
#   unset | false | warn (default) → log WARN, keep going; image
#                                    stays in Artifactory, job passes
#   true  | strict                 → fail the push step so CI marks
#                                    the job failed and downstream
#                                    promote/deploy jobs don't run.
# Non-violation scan errors (Xray offline, unlicensed, still indexing)
# always stay warnings regardless of this setting — they aren't
# policy decisions.
# ARTIFACTORY_XRAY_FAIL_ON_VIOLATIONS="false"

# ── JFrog CLI auto-install (sudoless) ─────────────────────────────
# If `jf` is not on PATH, the shared helper at scripts/lib/install-jf.sh
# installs it. Set ONE of the three URLs below — none = the build
# fails with a clear error. The public install-cli.jfrog.io path was
# removed because it requires sudo to mv the binary into /usr/local/bin
# and that's the original Bamboo blocker.
#
# All three paths land the binary at ${JF_INSTALL_DIR:-$HOME/.local/bin}
# without any privileged operation:
#   - JF_BINARY_URL: direct download
#   - JF_DEB_URL:    `dpkg-deb -x` (or `ar` + `tar` fallback)
#   - JF_RPM_URL:    `rpm2cpio | cpio`

# Direct URL to the standalone jf binary (PREFERRED — fastest, OS-agnostic).
# JF_BINARY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-releases-remote/jfrog-cli/v2-jf/2.103.0/jfrog-cli-linux-amd64/jf"

# Debian package URL (we extract jf with dpkg-deb -x, no install).
# Useful when your Artifactory mirrors JFrog's apt repo but not the
# raw binary.
# JF_DEB_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-debs/pool/jfrog-cli-v2-jf_2.103.0_amd64.deb"

# RPM package URL (we extract jf with rpm2cpio | cpio, no install).
# Same idea for RHEL-family.
# JF_RPM_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-rpms/jfrog-cli-v2-jf-2.103.0.x86_64.rpm"

# Where to install the jf binary. Default: ${HOME}/.local/bin (no sudo).
# Override to /usr/local/bin only when you specifically want it
# system-wide AND have sudo or are running as root.
# JF_INSTALL_DIR="${HOME}/.local/bin"
#
# ── Layout templates ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The backend has ZERO hardcoded repo paths. Both the docker push URL
# and the REST storage path (for property tagging) are resolved from
# shell parameter-expansion templates you supply via two variables:
#
#   ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF      docker push URL template
#   ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH  REST storage path for jf rt set-props
#
# Template variables available inside both:
#   ${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}    docker push hostname
#   ${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}         team acronym
#   ${ARTIFACTORY_ENVIRONMENT}  dev | prod
#   ${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}  dev→local, prod→prod (legacy helper)
#   ${IMAGE_NAME}               image short name (e.g. nginx)
#   ${IMAGE_TAG}                full computed tag (upstream+sha)
#
# Five named presets are documented below. Uncomment the one that
# matches your Artifactory layout. Leaving all five commented falls
# back to Layout A (per-team repo, backward compat with homelab).
#
# When setting these as GitLab CI variables, use raw=true to prevent
# GitLab from expanding the ${...} references. Or use $$ escaping
# when triggering via the pipeline API.
#
# ── Layout A: Per-team repos (default fallback) ──────────────────
#
#   Docker push:  <host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'
#
# ── Layout B: Shared repo with team subfolder ────────────────────
#
#   Docker push:  <host>/docker/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      docker/<team>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'
#
# ── Layout C: Subdomain-routed shared repo (JFrog recommended) ───
#
#   Docker push:  docker.<host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      docker/<team>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'
#
# ── Layout D: Subdomain-per-team ─────────────────────────────────
#
#   Docker push:  <team>.<host>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}.artifactory.example.com'
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'
#
# ── Layout E: Team-dispatch subdomain ────────────────────────────
#
#   Docker push:  docker.<host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#   (team segment stripped by sidecar — needs external nginx map)
#
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'
#
# ── Layout F: JFrog Cloud / Pro virtual repo (path-based) ────────
#
#   Docker push:  <host>/<virtual-repo>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <local-repo>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
#   Virtual routes to the backing local via defaultDeploymentRepo.
#
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="yourorg.jfrog.io"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-dev/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-dev-local/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# XRAY SCAN OVERRIDES (separate Artifactory for Xray)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# When the Artifactory you push to has no Xray license (e.g. JCR Free)
# but you have a separate Pro / Cloud trial that does, set these to
# point scan/xray-vuln.sh + scan/xray-sbom.sh at the scanning instance — the build job
# still pushes to ARTIFACTORY_URL above.
#
# Unset = scan/xray-vuln.sh + scan/xray-sbom.sh falls back to ARTIFACTORY_URL/USER/TOKEN
# (the same instance as push). Works fine when one Artifactory does both.
#
# Set as CI plan vars when the values are secrets — never commit tokens.
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_URL="https://myorg.jfrog.io"
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_USER="svc-xray"
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_TOKEN="eyJ2ZXIiOiIyIiwidHlwIjoiSldUIiwiYWxnIjoiUlMyNTYi..."

# Generate a CycloneDX SBOM via a SECOND `jf docker scan` call (with
# --format=cyclonedx --sbom). Costs one extra Xray scan (~50s on
# nginx) but produces the canonical sbom.cdx.json which sbom-post.sh
# ships to every configured sink.
#
# Default ON because Xray is the only approved SBOM source in
# environments where Trivy is banned and Syft awaits security review.
# Set to "false" when Syft is producing the SBOM and you don't want
# an Xray duplicate.
# XRAY_GENERATE_SBOM="true"

# Override the scan target. When unset, the scripts resolve in this
# order: $1 (positional arg) > XRAY_SCAN_REF > IMAGE_DIGEST > IMAGE_REF
# > UPSTREAM_REF > UPSTREAM_REGISTRY/IMAGE:TAG. Default behaviour
# scans the BUILT image (IMAGE_DIGEST from build.env) — that's what
# consumers pull, so it's what should be audited.
#
# Use this to point the scan elsewhere — common cases:
#   XRAY_SCAN_REF="docker.io/library/nginx:1.25.3-alpine"
#     (scan the upstream as a prescan gate before build runs)
#   XRAY_SCAN_REF="harbor.example.com/apps/platform/nginx@sha256:..."
#     (scan a specific previously-built digest)
# XRAY_SCAN_REF="docker.io/library/nginx:1.25.3-alpine"

# Policy gate — fail the scan job when matching severity vulns exist.
# Comma-separated, case-insensitive. Empty/unset = report-only mode
# (current default — produces JSON for SecOps but doesn't block).
#
# Examples:
#   XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="critical"            # only criticals fail
#   XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="critical,high"       # either fails
#   XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="critical,high,medium" # anything serious fails
#
# Wire this into a `prescan` stage to fail-fast on a bad upstream
# BEFORE rebuild, or into a `postscan` stage to block promotion of a
# built image that exceeds your CVE policy. The script exits 2 (not 1)
# on policy violation so CI can distinguish it from script errors.
# XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="critical,high"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SPLUNK HEC — jf docker scan audit ingestion
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# scripts/scan/xray-vuln.sh + scan/xray-sbom.sh runs `jf docker scan` against the upstream
# image and ships the result JSON to Splunk's HTTP Event Collector for
# audit / reporting. Wired into both pipelines as a separate stage; if
# either of these is unset, the stage is a no-op and exits 0.
#
# Set SPLUNK_HEC_TOKEN as a CI secret, NOT here.

# Full HEC URL — base is enough; /services/collector is appended if
# missing.
# SPLUNK_HEC_URL="https://splunk.example.com:8088"

# HEC token (do NOT commit — set via CI plan vars / project vars).
# Format is a UUID; sent as `Authorization: Splunk <token>`.
# SPLUNK_HEC_TOKEN="00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"

# Target index. Default: main
# SPLUNK_HEC_INDEX="security"

# Sourcetype tag (lets you write a Splunk props.conf for parsing).
# Default: jfrog:xray:scan
# SPLUNK_HEC_SOURCETYPE="jfrog:xray:scan"

# Set "true" to skip TLS verification (curl -k). Use only for self-signed
# Splunk on isolated networks.
# SPLUNK_HEC_INSECURE="false"

# Envelope `source` field prefix. The lib appends "-job" so the value
# in Splunk reads like "<prefix>-job", mimicking the
# /var/log/<source>-job.log convention. Default: pipeline → "pipeline-job".
# Override per fork to group dashboards/alerts by the owning pipeline,
# e.g. SPLUNK_SOURCE="cdss" → "cdss-job".
# SPLUNK_SOURCE="pipeline"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CANONICAL ARTIFACT FILENAMES (overrides — almost never needed)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Defaults live in scripts/lib/artifact-names.sh. Override only when
# a fork wants a non-standard name (e.g. running both Xray-vuln AND
# Trivy-vuln in the same job context where they'd otherwise collide).
# build.sh writes the resolved values into build.env so postscan
# stages that do `. ./build.env` see the same names.
#
# SBOM_FILE="sbom.cdx.json"        # CycloneDX SBOM (syft / xray / trivy)
# VULN_SCAN_FILE="vuln-scan.json"  # vuln scan output (xray / grype / trivy)

# When the SBOM producer should scan source code instead of an image:
#   SBOM_TARGET="source"   (syft-sbom.sh → dir:${REPO_ROOT})
# Default "image" — scan IMAGE_DIGEST/IMAGE_REF.
# SBOM_TARGET="image"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TRIVY (DORMANT — banned for business use, scaffold only)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# scripts/scan/trivy-vuln.sh + trivy-sbom.sh are pinned to v0.69.3
# (the last safe pre-compromise binary release). Bump only after
# vetting the upstream advisory list — see trivy-vuln.sh's docstring.
#
# TRIVY_VERSION="0.69.3"
# TRIVY_INSTALLER_URL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/aquasecurity/trivy/main/contrib/install.sh"
# TRIVY_BINARY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/generic-tools/trivy/0.69.3/trivy_0.69.3_Linux-64bit.tar.gz"
# TRIVY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="CRITICAL,HIGH"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# GRYPE (severity gate — opt-in)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Same exit-2-on-violation contract as XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY and
# TRIVY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY — three scanners, one gating convention.
# GRYPE_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="Critical,High"

# Override the Grype DB mirror subpath under ARTIFACTORY_GRYPE_DB_REPO
# (default "grype-db/v6"). Preserves Anchore's relative structure.
# GRYPE_DB_MIRROR_SUBPATH="grype-db/v6"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# DEBUG
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Verbose "why did this happen?" logging from build.sh. When true, the
# script prints which file was sourced, which env vars came from where,
# why each default was applied, and which install paths were attempted.
# Off by default to keep normal CI logs clean. Flip to true when
# troubleshooting "image.env is being ignored" / "INJECT_CERTS wouldn't
# turn off" / "tag suddenly changed shape" etc.
# BUILD_DEBUG="false"
